04701nam a22008055i 9780824863364DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t19951995hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1029820503  a(OCoLC)1032683153  a(OCoLC)1037902308  a(OCoLC)1041976797  a(OCoLC)1046613120  a(OCoLC)1047011515  a(OCoLC)1049611993  a(OCoLC)1054871458  a97808248633647 a10.1515/97808248633642doi  a(DE-B1597)484679  a(OCoLC)1024018695  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aJA84.C6bW66 1995eb 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a320/.09512201 aWood, Alan T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLimits to Autocracy :bFrom Sung Neo-Confucianism to a Doctrine of Political Rights /cAlan T. Wood. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[1995] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- tPart One. The Historical Dimension -- t2. The Background of Neo-Confucianism -- t3. Background of the Ch’un-ch’iu Commentaries -- tPart Two. The Ideological Dimension -- t4. Sun Fu’s Views on Obedience to Authority: The Literal/Moral Levels -- t5. The Views of Ch’eng I and Hu An-kuo: The Moral/Metaphysical Levels -- t6. Statecraft and Natural Law in the West and China -- t7. Implications for Modern China and Japan -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlan T. Wood examines the cultural identity of modern China in the context of authoritarianism in the Chinese political tradition. Taking on issues of key importance in the understanding of Chinese history, Wood leads readers to a reconsideration of neo-Confucian thinkers of the Northern Sung dynasty. Modern scholars have accused Sung neo-Confucians of advocating a doctrine of unconditional obedience to the ruler--of "revering the emperor and expelling the barbarian"--and thereby inhibiting the rise of democracy in China. Wood refutes this dominant view by arguing that Sung neo-Confucians intended to limit the power of the emperor, not enhance it. Sung political thinkers believed passionately in the existence of a moral cosmos governed by universal laws that transcended the ruler and could be invoked to set limits on his power. Wood makes a striking comparison of this view with a similar one of universal morality or natural law that developed in late Medieval Europe. By drawing attention to a much-neglected Confucian text, he contributes significantly to the wider dialog of human rights in China and brings forth fresh philosophical insights in his comparative view of Chinese and Western history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aNeo-Confucianism. 0aPolitical sciencezChinaxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311056415040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486336440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824863364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824863364/original  a978-3-11-056415-0  University of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Package  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK